    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. An escrow account is a neutral third-party account where funds are held during the closing process of a real estate transaction. The money is typically held by an escrow company or a title company, not by the real estate agent or the seller. This ensures that the funds are available to pay for the property and related expenses, such as taxes and insurance, once the transaction is complete.\n\nThe escrow company acts as a safeguard, releasing the funds only when all the necessary documents have been signed and the terms of the sale have been met. This includes the transfer of the property deed and the payment of any outstanding debts, such as your mortgage. The escrow company will provide you with a closing statement that details all the transactions and payments made during the process, giving you transparency and peace of mind.\n\nTo ensure that the funds are secure, you can check with the escrow company or title company handling your transaction. They should be able to provide you with information about the account and the steps they take to protect your money. Additionally, you can review the closing statement and any other documentation provided to you during the process to verify that everything is in order.",
